Well the real bug is that bitcoind closes the connection and python-bitcoinlib doesn't notice.  The next time the client tries to make an rpc call, it throws an exception.  As far as I'm concerned this is a bug to pass responsibility for reopening connections to the caller.

@stefanlenoach what do you think about: Upon proxy.call, check if the connection is open.  If not, open a new one and issue the call.  This avoids potentially problematic retrying, but won't handle flaky connections -- if the connection is terminated in an unusual manner, it's still the caller's logic that decides whether to resubmit the transaction, or re-request data.

The case we're concerned about here is not an *unusual* close, it's the regular and well behaved close by bitcoind when it times out.

Hey @rajasaur. Are you familiar with api.ai's [folluw-up intents](https://api.ai/docs/intents#follow-up_intents) and [events](https://api.ai/docs/events)?These may to be a better match for your situation than alternating/stacking different contexts for the series of questions.

Events simply allow you to basically call another intent from within your action, while followups are intents that are triggered directly after a given intent. You can define both events and followups in the api.ai console, but currently not from flask-assistant. (Follow up intents are just events behind the scenes)


You can create 'yes' and 'no' fallback intents as well as custom ones. These can pass entities to your action functions just like regular intents.

Inside your webhook you can use followups like this:

```
@assist.action('AskFries')
def ask_for_fries():
    return ask('Would you like fries with that?')

@assist.action('AskFries - yes')
def ask_to_supersize():
    return ask('Do you want to supersize it?)

@assist.action('AskFries - no')
def answer_for_no():
    return tell('ok, your total is $4')


```

You can also stack followup intents
```
@assist.action('AskFries')
def ask_for_fries():
    return ask('Would you like fries with that?')

@assist.action('AskFries - yes')
def ask_to_supersize():
    return ask('Do you want to supersize it?)

@assist.action('AskFries - yes - yes') # default name created inside API.AI
def finish_order():
    return tell('Nice, ill make them supersized')

@assist.action('AskFries - yes - no') # default name created inside API.AI
def finish_order():
    return tell('ok, one regular fry.')
```

You can change the followup intent's name inside the api.ai console:
```
@assist.action('AskFriesSupersized')  # was 'AskFries - yes'
def ask_followup_question():
    return ask('Do you want to supersize it?)

@assist.action('ConfirmSuperSize')  # instead of 'AskFries - yes - yes'
def finish_order():
    return tell('Nice, ill make them supersized')

@assist.action('ConfirmRegularFry')  # instead of 'AskFries - yes - no'
def finish_order():
    return tell('ok, one regular fry.')
```

 Or use events instead of stacking followups
 ```
 from flask_assistant import ask, tell, event

@assist.action('AskFries')
def ask_for_fries():
    return ask('Would you like fries with that?')

@assist.action('AskFries - yes')
def ask_to_super_fries():
    return event('AskSuperSize')

@assist.action('AskFries - no')
def move_onto_soda():
    return event('AskSoda')

@assist.action('AskSupersize') # Intent has an event defined in console
def ask_to_supersize():
    return ask('Do you want to supersize it?)

# ... follow up intents

@assist.action('AskSoda') # Intent has an event defined in console
def ask_for_soda():
    return ask('Would you like a soda?')

# ... followup intents
```

