Note that `PyObject_IsTrue` can fail, e.g. `bool(np.array([...]))` raises an exception.

```c++
if (convert) {
    auto result = PyObject_IsTrue(src.ptr());
    if (result == -1)  // this *should* also cover missing `__bool__`/`__nonzero__`, 
        return false;  // but adding a proper test to make sure would be good
    value = result == 1;
    return true;
}
```

@pde, yeah. I was specifically trying to fix the error messages reported in the two issues I claimed to be fixing. They are the most common error messages for people when they run the client without root.

In general, such errors could occur all over the place. Any time we access a file or grab a port, there's a chance we could have insufficient privileges. If we wanted to catch all `IOError` and `OSError` exceptions that could ever occur within the program, I could add another case to `_handle_exception` and add the message there.

I think the problem with doing this though is in many contexts, the message doesn't make sense. If you're trying to use the standalone, Nginx, or Apache plugins without root, you're going to have a bad time. Changing the default directories isn't going to fix that. If we want to do more than what's done in this PR, I think we have to look at each case individually and write an error message that describes that specific problem.

